WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.345 --> 00:00:03.330
CHRIS DEFAY: All right, hello,
my name's Chris DeFay.

00:00:03.330 --> 00:00:06.200
And this is a Talks at Google
Presentation here in Google's

00:00:06.200 --> 00:00:07.810
Los Angeles office.

00:00:07.810 --> 00:00:10.840
We are very pleased today to
welcome author and musician

00:00:10.840 --> 00:00:11.990
Ian Whitcomb.

00:00:11.990 --> 00:00:14.620
Ian is a native of Surrey,
England, and a current

00:00:14.620 --> 00:00:17.430
resident of Altadena, northeast
of downtown Los

00:00:17.430 --> 00:00:19.210
Angeles, and has been
entertaining

00:00:19.210 --> 00:00:20.860
the world for decades.

00:00:20.860 --> 00:00:25.240
After hitting the American Top
10 charts in 1965 with his

00:00:25.240 --> 00:00:29.060
novelty record "You Turn Me On"
and finding himself in the

00:00:29.060 --> 00:00:33.230
company of young bands like The
Rolling Stones, he devoted

00:00:33.230 --> 00:00:36.250
his work to resurrecting the
roots of pop music, especially

00:00:36.250 --> 00:00:38.530
ragtime and Tin Pan Alley.

00:00:38.530 --> 00:00:40.960
He's performed everywhere, from
the Hollywood Bowl, to

00:00:40.960 --> 00:00:43.650
the Montreux Jazz Festival,
and has appeared on Johnny

00:00:43.650 --> 00:00:46.690
Carson, "The Tonight Show." As
an author he has published

00:00:46.690 --> 00:00:49.890
over 20 books, and is best known
for his book, "After the

00:00:49.890 --> 00:00:53.060
Ball," on the history of pop
music from rag to rock.

00:00:53.060 --> 00:00:55.600
Today he will be discussing the
topic of his recent book,

00:00:55.600 --> 00:00:58.430
"Ukulele Heroes, the Golden
Age," and playing us a few

00:00:58.430 --> 00:00:59.320
samples, I think.

00:00:59.320 --> 00:01:00.080
IAN WHITCOMB: I'll try.

00:01:00.080 --> 00:01:01.010
CHRIS DEFAY: Yes.

00:01:01.010 --> 00:01:03.100
Please join me in
welcoming Ian.

00:01:03.100 --> 00:01:04.012
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:04.012 --> 00:01:06.292
IAN WHITCOMB: Thank you.

00:01:06.292 --> 00:01:07.940
First of all, how
many of you here

00:01:07.940 --> 00:01:10.270
actually play the ukulele?

00:01:10.270 --> 00:01:12.860
Good, great, well I used to
be a very good player.

00:01:12.860 --> 00:01:15.780
But I had an illness, and
I can't strum very well.

00:01:15.780 --> 00:01:16.680
Here's the ukulele.

00:01:16.680 --> 00:01:21.560
This is a Martin, one of the
best ones you can get.

00:01:21.560 --> 00:01:22.600
It's nice.

00:01:22.600 --> 00:01:25.090
I call this a pleasingly
plangent sound.

00:01:25.090 --> 00:01:30.090
[UKULELE PLAYING]

00:01:30.090 --> 00:01:31.770
IAN WHITCOMB: So it's a
four-stringed instrument.

00:01:31.770 --> 00:01:34.070
And I'll give you a little brief
history, but not too

00:01:34.070 --> 00:01:34.450
much of it.

00:01:34.450 --> 00:01:36.160
I want to questions
from you all too.

00:01:36.160 --> 00:01:39.180
Brief history is that it was
actually not invented in

00:01:39.180 --> 00:01:40.280
Hawaii at all.

00:01:40.280 --> 00:01:42.140
It was invented by
the Portuguese.

00:01:42.140 --> 00:01:43.540
It was called a machete there.

00:01:43.540 --> 00:01:46.750
In fact, there's a picture in
1860 of the girl who became

00:01:46.750 --> 00:01:50.860
Alice in "Alice in Wonderland"
playing her machete.

00:01:50.860 --> 00:01:54.430
And it was brought across to
Hawaii by Portuguese who were

00:01:54.430 --> 00:01:57.000
working in the plantations then,
the sugar plantations.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:00.360
And they had four of them on
board a ship called the

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:03.800
"Raven's Crag," which
had arrived in 1878.

00:02:03.800 --> 00:02:07.050
And the Hawaiians immediately
took to this instrument, which

00:02:07.050 --> 00:02:09.709
they called it ukulele, or
oo-kah-lay-lee, as they say in

00:02:09.709 --> 00:02:12.370
Hawaii, which means jumping
or leaping flea.

00:02:12.370 --> 00:02:15.210
And they loved it, especially
the royalty, Hawaiian royalty.

00:02:15.210 --> 00:02:16.500
At that time it was
a free country.

00:02:16.500 --> 00:02:19.590
That was just before America
came in and acquired, well,

00:02:19.590 --> 00:02:21.980
shall we say they overthrew
the queen.

00:02:21.980 --> 00:02:22.630
We won't go into that.

00:02:22.630 --> 00:02:24.070
It's a sore point
for Hawaiians.

00:02:24.070 --> 00:02:27.440
It was a bloodless revolution,
or rebellion, or whatever,

00:02:27.440 --> 00:02:29.550
takeover , by American
businessmen in

00:02:29.550 --> 00:02:30.450
the pineapple business.

00:02:30.450 --> 00:02:32.670
But anyway, it's
all in my book.

00:02:32.670 --> 00:02:36.030
The point is the last queen,
whose name I can't pronounce,

00:02:36.030 --> 00:02:37.170
who's on the cover of my book.

00:02:37.170 --> 00:02:38.210
I should know her name.

00:02:38.210 --> 00:02:39.700
Some of you may know her name.

00:02:39.700 --> 00:02:41.390
She was a wonderful composer.

00:02:41.390 --> 00:02:42.740
And she wrote great songs.

00:02:42.740 --> 00:02:45.470
She wrote the famous "Aloha
Oe." It sounds Jewish.

00:02:45.470 --> 00:02:50.320
It's not, "Aloha Oe." And
she played the piano.

00:02:50.320 --> 00:02:53.390
And she survived the overthrow
of the country.

00:02:53.390 --> 00:02:55.530
The steel guitar, by the
way, was actually

00:02:55.530 --> 00:02:56.890
invented by the Hawaiians.

00:02:56.890 --> 00:03:00.660
That's where you pull a metal
bar across the strings.

00:03:00.660 --> 00:03:01.720
They did actually invent that.

00:03:01.720 --> 00:03:02.820
They didn't invent
the ukulele.

00:03:02.820 --> 00:03:06.630
But they did invent this slide
guitar, which, of course, is

00:03:06.630 --> 00:03:09.060
now associated very much
with blues and country.

00:03:09.060 --> 00:03:10.600
But it actually comes
from Hawaii.

00:03:10.600 --> 00:03:12.810
So they can claim that one.

00:03:12.810 --> 00:03:16.790
I won't get too historical, but
what happened was that,

00:03:16.790 --> 00:03:20.600
eventually, the mainlanders, as
they call us, got to hear

00:03:20.600 --> 00:03:21.550
about the ukulele.

00:03:21.550 --> 00:03:24.150
In 1915, there was an exposition
in San Francisco

00:03:24.150 --> 00:03:26.590
called the Pan-Pacific
Exposition.

00:03:26.590 --> 00:03:29.620
And the Hawaiians had
their own pavilion.

00:03:29.620 --> 00:03:32.990
And they sent across their
bands, which were the most

00:03:32.990 --> 00:03:35.370
popular things of all, these
Hawaiian bands with ukuleles

00:03:35.370 --> 00:03:36.190
and steel guitars.

00:03:36.190 --> 00:03:39.075
And, more importantly, hula
girls swaying because the

00:03:39.075 --> 00:03:41.720
hula, although it's a religious
dance, we see it as

00:03:41.720 --> 00:03:43.160
sort of a sexy dance
from the hips.

00:03:43.160 --> 00:03:44.320
But the Hawaiians don't
think that.

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:45.840
They think it's a very
religious dance.

00:03:45.840 --> 00:03:49.110
Anyway, the hula girls and the
Hawaiian bands were extremely

00:03:49.110 --> 00:03:51.080
popular in America in 1915.

00:03:51.080 --> 00:03:54.930
So much so that Tin Pan Alley,
in New York where they wrote-

00:03:54.930 --> 00:03:56.640
I guess you all know what
Tin Pan Alley is.

00:03:56.640 --> 00:03:59.200
It's where they manufactured
popular songs.

00:03:59.200 --> 00:04:02.070
They were all published
in sheet music form.

00:04:02.070 --> 00:04:05.010
And Tin Pan Alley realized
this was a phenomena.

00:04:05.010 --> 00:04:08.710
So they started writing songs
about Hawaii and what a

00:04:08.710 --> 00:04:10.240
blissful place it was.

00:04:10.240 --> 00:04:13.690
So Hawaiian bands toured
America, became very popular,

00:04:13.690 --> 00:04:16.880
especially in the south, where
the southerners loved the

00:04:16.880 --> 00:04:17.480
steel guitar.

00:04:17.480 --> 00:04:20.790
And that's why you have the
steel guitar in country music,

00:04:20.790 --> 00:04:22.770
because of Hawaiian bands
touring the country.

00:04:22.770 --> 00:04:26.030
Now I should just tell you
about myself a bit more.

00:04:26.030 --> 00:04:29.460
I was, as what Chris explained,
I was a teen idol

00:04:29.460 --> 00:04:31.340
for a short time in the '60s.

00:04:31.340 --> 00:04:33.290
Probably nobody remembers "You
Turn Me On," do they?

00:04:33.290 --> 00:04:35.050
Anybody remember that song,
"You Turn Me On"?

00:04:35.050 --> 00:04:37.630
It was top 10, top
number eight.

00:04:37.630 --> 00:04:39.080
I think you do.

00:04:39.080 --> 00:04:42.530
In 1965, I was in the top 10,
the same time that the song

00:04:42.530 --> 00:04:44.380
"Satisfaction" was number one.

00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:46.680
Anyway, quickly I realized
that rock and

00:04:46.680 --> 00:04:48.530
roll was not my field.

00:04:48.530 --> 00:04:49.480
So I started--

00:04:49.480 --> 00:04:53.160
I bought a ukulele in a
pawnshop, P-A-W-N, in Los

00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:54.640
Angeles, a Martin.

00:04:54.640 --> 00:04:57.260
And I immediately began playing
the uke on the bus

00:04:57.260 --> 00:04:59.030
tours that I did with these
rock and roll groups.

00:04:59.030 --> 00:05:01.615
And a group called The Turtles
heard me and said, you ought

00:05:01.615 --> 00:05:03.940
to record some of these songs.

00:05:03.940 --> 00:05:04.470
So I did.

00:05:04.470 --> 00:05:06.800
I've been recording the
older songs since.

00:05:06.800 --> 00:05:09.375
And my whole career has gone
backwards because of that.

00:05:09.375 --> 00:05:11.200
But I was playing ukulele.

00:05:11.200 --> 00:05:14.940
And my version of this 1916
song, "Where Did Robinson

00:05:14.940 --> 00:05:19.760
Crusoe Go with Friday on
Saturday Night?" became a hit

00:05:19.760 --> 00:05:21.940
and established me
as a uke player.

00:05:21.940 --> 00:05:24.990
And I suppose, in a way, I
started the whole uke revival

00:05:24.990 --> 00:05:28.330
because this was before Tiny
Tim, who is associated with--

00:05:28.330 --> 00:05:32.550
This is from a song book I've
got out called "Ian Whitcomb's

00:05:32.550 --> 00:05:35.760
Ukulele Sing-Along." It's a
nice little book with a CD

00:05:35.760 --> 00:05:38.300
attached, which you
can get online.

00:05:38.300 --> 00:05:40.270
And it sells quite well.

00:05:40.270 --> 00:05:44.080
Anyway, we've reached the point
where Tin Pan Alley is

00:05:44.080 --> 00:05:46.080
cashing in on the
Hawaiian craze.

00:05:46.080 --> 00:05:48.800
And in America, people
are buying ukuleles.

00:05:48.800 --> 00:05:53.820
The Martin company begins
to build the ukulele.

00:05:53.820 --> 00:05:57.170
If you have any questions ask
them anytime you like.

00:05:57.170 --> 00:05:58.360
So, yes, a question?

00:05:58.360 --> 00:06:03.270
AUDIENCE: Did you say a date or
a decade when the ukulele

00:06:03.270 --> 00:06:07.689
was introduced by the Portuguese
to Hawaii?

00:06:07.689 --> 00:06:09.940
IAN WHITCOMB: Yes, well they
came over in a ship, the three

00:06:09.940 --> 00:06:13.710
of them, in 1878, in the
"Raven's Crag." They landed in

00:06:13.710 --> 00:06:16.150
Hawaii, in Honolulu.

00:06:16.150 --> 00:06:18.230
And they were all craftsmen.

00:06:18.230 --> 00:06:19.630
They had the ukuleles
with them.

00:06:19.630 --> 00:06:20.820
And many of them could
build ukes.

00:06:20.820 --> 00:06:25.430
And so the first ukuleles were
built by Portuguese craftsmen.

00:06:25.430 --> 00:06:28.310
And then they gradually, as I
said, it became popular from

00:06:28.310 --> 00:06:29.810
about 1915.

00:06:29.810 --> 00:06:33.300
And then the mainlanders
began to make ukes.

00:06:33.300 --> 00:06:35.230
Although Hawaii still makes
very good ukes.

00:06:35.230 --> 00:06:37.445
If you want to buy one, by the
way, my friend who put this

00:06:37.445 --> 00:06:40.920
out, Jim Beloff has a very good
company called Fluke,

00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:44.330
F-L-U-K-E, and they make
really good ukes.

00:06:44.330 --> 00:06:46.420
They're designed by
an MIT engineer.

00:06:46.420 --> 00:06:47.950
They're partly wood and
partly plastic.

00:06:47.950 --> 00:06:50.030
They have a beautiful sound.

00:06:50.030 --> 00:06:51.550
So that's Jim Beloff.

00:06:51.550 --> 00:06:53.220
His email address is
fleamarketmusic.com.

00:06:56.820 --> 00:06:58.345
AUDIENCE: I was curious because
Mark Twain was in

00:06:58.345 --> 00:06:59.605
Hawaii in the 1860s.

00:06:59.605 --> 00:07:02.530
I was wondering if he
would have heard it.

00:07:02.530 --> 00:07:04.670
IAN WHITCOMB: There wouldn't
have been a ukulele then.

00:07:04.670 --> 00:07:06.370
The Portuguese had
it in the 1860s.

00:07:06.370 --> 00:07:07.550
It was called a machete.

00:07:07.550 --> 00:07:09.555
It never really caught on.

00:07:09.555 --> 00:07:12.480
It was only when the Portuguese

00:07:12.480 --> 00:07:13.440
brought it to Hawaii.

00:07:13.440 --> 00:07:15.580
And then the Hawaiians
loved it.

00:07:15.580 --> 00:07:19.890
They called it the ukulele,
jumping flea, and then it got

00:07:19.890 --> 00:07:20.920
popularized from then.

00:07:20.920 --> 00:07:24.070
They really developed the
whole strumming style.

00:07:24.070 --> 00:07:24.440
Yes?

00:07:24.440 --> 00:07:27.470
AUDIENCE: Did they keep
the same tuning?

00:07:27.470 --> 00:07:29.670
IAN WHITCOMB: No, the original
tuning was different.

00:07:29.670 --> 00:07:33.010
That tuning I have there is the
standard, G-C-E-A, my dog

00:07:33.010 --> 00:07:36.820
has fleas, but in the old days,
the early days it was

00:07:36.820 --> 00:07:39.455
actually different tuning.

00:07:39.455 --> 00:07:40.815
It was much higher.

00:07:40.815 --> 00:07:42.920
But it got standardized.

00:07:42.920 --> 00:07:44.770
If you look at old sheet music,
you'll see that they

00:07:44.770 --> 00:07:46.520
have from the '20s onwards--

00:07:49.390 --> 00:07:51.630
I'm playing around with
my technology--

00:07:51.630 --> 00:07:53.750
if you look at the old sheet
music, and today, they have

00:07:53.750 --> 00:07:56.600
these little grids that show you
where to put your fingers.

00:07:56.600 --> 00:07:58.840
Those were invented
about 1920.

00:07:58.840 --> 00:08:01.260
And if you look at any old sheet
music from that period,

00:08:01.260 --> 00:08:02.770
it'd say ukulele arrangement.

00:08:02.770 --> 00:08:04.600
The reason is, and I should
get back to this point, is

00:08:04.600 --> 00:08:07.540
that by that time the ukulele
had become really popular,

00:08:07.540 --> 00:08:08.880
very trendy.

00:08:08.880 --> 00:08:11.360
In the 1920s, in the Jazz Age,
it was the trend to play a

00:08:11.360 --> 00:08:13.810
saxophone, or play the drums,
or play the ukulele.

00:08:13.810 --> 00:08:16.470
That's why you see these young
men in raccoon cotes playing

00:08:16.470 --> 00:08:16.970
the ukulele.

00:08:16.970 --> 00:08:18.890
It was the way to woo
your girlfriend.

00:08:18.890 --> 00:08:20.240
In fact, I have experience
with that

00:08:20.240 --> 00:08:23.120
because- not in the 20s.

00:08:23.120 --> 00:08:24.810
But when I had a-- before
I met Regina,

00:08:24.810 --> 00:08:27.000
I had a lady friend.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:31.460
I once sang on the beach to her,
you were meant for me,

00:08:31.460 --> 00:08:34.580
with my uke, and she
took it seriously.

00:08:34.580 --> 00:08:36.470
She said, do you mean that?

00:08:36.470 --> 00:08:37.659
Are you serious about that?

00:08:37.659 --> 00:08:40.520
I realized then the power of
these old popular songs.

00:08:40.520 --> 00:08:42.030
They're very powerful songs.

00:08:42.030 --> 00:08:44.150
It doesn't apply today, because
people shout today,

00:08:44.150 --> 00:08:44.730
and they rant.

00:08:44.730 --> 00:08:46.340
And I can't understand what
they're talking about.

00:08:46.340 --> 00:08:48.980
But in those days there were
very romantic songs, which hit

00:08:48.980 --> 00:08:51.160
the nail squarely on the head.

00:08:51.160 --> 00:08:51.980
So I love those songs.

00:08:51.980 --> 00:08:55.100
That's why I'm still very
involved with old songs.

00:08:55.100 --> 00:08:56.420
I write books about songs.

00:08:56.420 --> 00:08:57.940
I love old songs.

00:08:57.940 --> 00:09:00.810
By the way, if you go on
YouTube, you can see some

00:09:00.810 --> 00:09:03.630
videos I made with an Akai.

00:09:03.630 --> 00:09:05.940
I don't know if you know the
Akai, reel to reel, was an

00:09:05.940 --> 00:09:08.780
early prototype video recorder,
portable one.

00:09:08.780 --> 00:09:11.260
I had one and I went to New York
with it, and I videoed

00:09:11.260 --> 00:09:14.280
all the old songwriters I could
find, including the man

00:09:14.280 --> 00:09:18.430
who wrote "Swanny" with George
Gershwin, Irving Caesar..

00:09:18.430 --> 00:09:22.090
And these are all up online
now on YouTube.

00:09:22.090 --> 00:09:23.390
You can see me.

00:09:23.390 --> 00:09:26.800
You can see my interview with
Johnny Marks, who wrote

00:09:26.800 --> 00:09:29.150
"Rudolph, the Red-Nosed
Reindeer." You can see me--

00:09:29.150 --> 00:09:30.120
if you type in--

00:09:30.120 --> 00:09:31.350
I think he's doing it now.

00:09:31.350 --> 00:09:33.710
Type in Ian Whitcomb, Harry
Warren, who's a great

00:09:33.710 --> 00:09:36.280
songwriter, who wrote "Home in
Pasadena." You can see he and

00:09:36.280 --> 00:09:37.870
I singing that song together.

00:09:37.870 --> 00:09:40.170
And I'm accompanying
him on the ukulele.

00:09:40.170 --> 00:09:42.370
He sings what he calls
an obbligato part.

00:09:42.370 --> 00:09:42.980
He was a great man.

00:09:42.980 --> 00:09:46.146
So I, early on, when these
songwriters were still alive,

00:09:46.146 --> 00:09:47.130
I took my video camera.

00:09:47.130 --> 00:09:49.580
And I videoed them, as
many as I could.

00:09:49.580 --> 00:09:52.700
Eubie Blake, who lived to
be 100, I videoed him.

00:09:52.700 --> 00:09:54.090
I wish I'd done more of this.

00:09:54.090 --> 00:09:55.000
I mean, they're all dead now.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:59.090
But it was a wonderful- I was
so glad that I did that.

00:09:59.090 --> 00:10:00.855
G-C-E-A. [SINGING]

00:10:00.855 --> 00:10:04.705
My dog has fleas, fleas,
my dog has fleas.

00:10:04.705 --> 00:10:06.560
And it's easy to play.

00:10:06.560 --> 00:10:09.570
The basic, the first
C chord is--

00:10:09.570 --> 00:10:10.600
[UKULELE PLAYING]

00:10:10.600 --> 00:10:12.100
IAN WHITCOMB: And then G 7th.

00:10:12.100 --> 00:10:13.320
[UKULELE PLAYING]

00:10:13.320 --> 00:10:13.930
IAN WHITCOMB: F.

00:10:13.930 --> 00:10:24.910
[UKULELE PLAYING]

00:10:24.910 --> 00:10:26.160
IAN WHITCOMB: Pleasant
sound, isn't it?

