I used to be much stronger.

00:10:30.460 --> 00:10:32.320
But I had an illness.

00:10:32.320 --> 00:10:33.960
Which I'm recovering from,
by the way, folks.

00:10:33.960 --> 00:10:34.715
I'll just tell you know.

00:10:34.715 --> 00:10:37.180
I had a stroke about
nine months ago.

00:10:37.180 --> 00:10:38.460
So I'm doing my best.

00:10:38.460 --> 00:10:40.110
I hope you can understand
what I'm saying.

00:10:40.110 --> 00:10:41.680
I survived the stroke.

00:10:41.680 --> 00:10:42.410
But I'm still--

00:10:42.410 --> 00:10:44.330
my fingers are still bad.

00:10:44.330 --> 00:10:46.350
I can't feel much
in this hand.

00:10:46.350 --> 00:10:47.960
They keep telling me it
will all come back.

00:10:47.960 --> 00:10:49.920
I'm working on it every day.

00:10:49.920 --> 00:10:50.790
My wife's a great help.

00:10:50.790 --> 00:10:53.050
Anyway, got that
out of the way.

00:10:53.050 --> 00:10:53.830
I'm still performing.

00:10:53.830 --> 00:10:54.970
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:10:54.970 --> 00:10:57.050
IAN WHITCOMB: I'm left-handed.

00:10:57.050 --> 00:10:58.970
I'm left-handed, so it means
that I can't play the piano

00:10:58.970 --> 00:10:59.850
well now with my left hand.

00:10:59.850 --> 00:11:01.900
But I won't go into all that.

00:11:01.900 --> 00:11:02.460
I've survived.

00:11:02.460 --> 00:11:03.195
And I can talk.

00:11:03.195 --> 00:11:03.610
And I can walk.

00:11:03.610 --> 00:11:06.590
And I can be annoying.

00:11:06.590 --> 00:11:10.860
By the way, I'm sorry
I'm plugging myself.

00:11:10.860 --> 00:11:12.600
But if you're interested, I
have a radio show every

00:11:12.600 --> 00:11:16.650
Wednesday night on a site
called Luxuriamusic.com.

00:11:16.650 --> 00:11:19.150
It's a nice company,
LuxuriaMusic.

00:11:19.150 --> 00:11:19.880
And I do it live.

00:11:19.880 --> 00:11:21.950
It'll be on tomorrow night,
Wednesday night.

00:11:21.950 --> 00:11:24.250
If you really enjoy what I'm
saying, if you go online and

00:11:24.250 --> 00:11:27.400
just put in Ian Whitcomb
podcast, there are 93 radio

00:11:27.400 --> 00:11:29.550
shows that I did for XM.

00:11:29.550 --> 00:11:31.630
I used to work for
a company called

00:11:31.630 --> 00:11:34.220
Premiere Radio Networks.

00:11:34.220 --> 00:11:36.810
And amongst the radio shows
they make the most

00:11:36.810 --> 00:11:37.750
money off, not mine.

00:11:37.750 --> 00:11:40.040
They make money off Rush
Limbaugh, Sean Hannity--

00:11:40.040 --> 00:11:44.360
Years to come, because the
CDs will all fade.

00:11:44.360 --> 00:11:49.640
We'll be left with LPs, which
will last forever, and '78s,

00:11:49.640 --> 00:11:53.380
which, if you're careful with
them, are wonderful things.

00:11:53.380 --> 00:11:56.010
That's my little speech
about technology.

00:11:56.010 --> 00:11:57.870
I never understood why I see
all these kids going around

00:11:57.870 --> 00:11:59.680
with these things stuck in their
ears because the sound

00:11:59.680 --> 00:12:01.430
on MP3s is terrible.

00:12:01.430 --> 00:12:03.350
They'll never hear what good
sound sounds like.

00:12:03.350 --> 00:12:07.080
Good sound is an LP played
through a good turntable.

00:12:07.080 --> 00:12:07.720
That's what I think.

00:12:07.720 --> 00:12:11.040
And if you've got anything to
challenge me on that tell me.

00:12:11.040 --> 00:12:12.060
I'm an old technologist.

00:12:12.060 --> 00:12:13.035
I prefer old technology.

00:12:13.035 --> 00:12:17.148
AUDIENCE: Are you going to talk
later about certain, more

00:12:17.148 --> 00:12:20.211
recent resurgences
of the ukulele?

00:12:20.211 --> 00:12:22.290
IAN WHITCOMB: Well,
I do in the book.

00:12:22.290 --> 00:12:24.080
Of course, there's been
the resurgence.

00:12:24.080 --> 00:12:24.790
I didn't get to that.

00:12:24.790 --> 00:12:27.680
Sorry, I should quickly skip
to that before we get onto

00:12:27.680 --> 00:12:29.030
Ukulele Ike.

00:12:29.030 --> 00:12:31.215
Well, the ukulele was very
popular, as I was saying, in

00:12:31.215 --> 00:12:33.680
the '20s and the '30s.

00:12:33.680 --> 00:12:35.510
And then it started
to fade away.

00:12:35.510 --> 00:12:37.325
And with the coming of
rock and roll, it

00:12:37.325 --> 00:12:38.100
was completely out.

00:12:38.100 --> 00:12:41.270
When I was playing the
ukulele in the '60s,

00:12:41.270 --> 00:12:43.070
people laughed at me.

00:12:43.070 --> 00:12:44.040
It became a joke instrument.

00:12:44.040 --> 00:12:45.860
Of course, Tiny Tim
didn't help that.

00:12:45.860 --> 00:12:48.530
And it went out for a while
until the resurgence, which is

00:12:48.530 --> 00:12:51.320
started on this West Coast,
which is where most new things

00:12:51.320 --> 00:12:53.030
begin, on the West Coast.

00:12:53.030 --> 00:12:55.560
LA is a much better place than
New York, by the way.

00:12:55.560 --> 00:12:59.620
This is where we develop the
new things, in LA and

00:12:59.620 --> 00:13:00.540
California.

00:13:00.540 --> 00:13:02.870
Anyway, it started to
have a comeback.

00:13:02.870 --> 00:13:04.050
It's huge now.

00:13:04.050 --> 00:13:06.380
Everybody's playing
the ukulele.

00:13:06.380 --> 00:13:09.490
Warren Buffett plays it.

00:13:09.490 --> 00:13:13.900
And, as I was saying before,
if you watch any Pixar film

00:13:13.900 --> 00:13:15.650
they always have a ukulele
in every scene.

00:13:15.650 --> 00:13:16.890
They love ukulele.

00:13:16.890 --> 00:13:19.670
They hired me to come up there
and teach them to teach the

00:13:19.670 --> 00:13:21.800
directors to play the ukulele.

00:13:21.800 --> 00:13:24.040
So it's having a huge
comeback, why?

00:13:24.040 --> 00:13:26.000
Because it's very simple.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:29.290
It may be something to
do with the economy.

00:13:29.290 --> 00:13:30.563
It's an easy instrument
to play.

00:13:30.563 --> 00:13:31.280
You don't have to plug it in.

00:13:31.280 --> 00:13:34.790
You don't have to buy
amplifiers and have

00:13:34.790 --> 00:13:36.510
complicated, sophisticated
equipment.

00:13:36.510 --> 00:13:37.910
It's easy to play.

00:13:37.910 --> 00:13:39.260
And it's very pleasant.

00:13:39.260 --> 00:13:40.480
Everybody loves the
sound of it.

00:13:40.480 --> 00:13:42.420
It's a very, very peaceful
instrument.

00:13:42.420 --> 00:13:44.930
I believe the whole world's
problems of the world could be

00:13:44.930 --> 00:13:47.630
solved if we all just marched
into trouble spots with our

00:13:47.630 --> 00:13:49.870
ukes and just strummed.

00:13:49.870 --> 00:13:50.720
I say that in the book.

00:13:50.720 --> 00:13:53.230
I get into that in the book.

00:13:53.230 --> 00:13:53.925
Yes, Regina?

00:13:53.925 --> 00:13:57.687
REGINA: Taylor Swift says, right
from the stage when she

00:13:57.687 --> 00:14:02.760
plays the ukulele, she thinks
it has the friendliest sound

00:14:02.760 --> 00:14:04.065
of any instrument.

00:14:04.065 --> 00:14:06.260
IAN WHITCOMB: It's
very friendly.

00:14:06.260 --> 00:14:08.210
You couldn't hit anybody
with a ukulele.

00:14:08.210 --> 00:14:09.520
You couldn't rob them
or murder them.

00:14:09.520 --> 00:14:10.675
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:10.675 --> 00:14:12.380
IAN WHITCOMB: It's a very
safe instrument to play.

00:14:12.380 --> 00:14:13.490
I know.

00:14:13.490 --> 00:14:16.740
But anyway, I was saying- did
I explain the resurgence

00:14:16.740 --> 00:14:18.376
properly, sir?

00:14:18.376 --> 00:14:22.090
AUDIENCE: The other thing I've
noticed is that teenagers,

00:14:22.090 --> 00:14:25.350
like anything else, and maybe
this hasn't contributed to the

00:14:25.350 --> 00:14:28.337
popularity, but most teens that
I know that have picked

00:14:28.337 --> 00:14:31.584
it up at least began
to learn through

00:14:31.584 --> 00:14:32.875
watching YouTube videos.

00:14:32.875 --> 00:14:34.122
There's thousands of hours.

00:14:34.122 --> 00:14:37.420
IAN WHITCOMB: YouTube has lots
of videos of people playing

00:14:37.420 --> 00:14:38.740
it, how to play.

00:14:38.740 --> 00:14:41.240
It's an easy instrument
to play.

00:14:41.240 --> 00:14:41.940
Anybody can play it.

00:14:41.940 --> 00:14:44.245
It's great fun just to learn
a few chords and

00:14:44.245 --> 00:14:45.725
sing along at parties.

00:14:45.725 --> 00:14:47.950
It's so popular.

00:14:47.950 --> 00:14:51.120
As I said, I feel that I did
play a little small part in

00:14:51.120 --> 00:14:52.970
having it become
popular again.

00:14:52.970 --> 00:14:55.340
And I've always loved
the sound of it.

00:14:55.340 --> 00:14:57.230
You can play any chord
on the uke.

00:14:57.230 --> 00:14:58.120
It's a wonderful instrument.

00:14:58.120 --> 00:15:00.590
Well, let's just get back to
the '20s if I may, and hear

00:15:00.590 --> 00:15:01.200
Ukulele Ike.

00:15:01.200 --> 00:15:02.710
We talked about scat singing.

00:15:02.710 --> 00:15:05.750
He did this- he called
it eefing.

00:15:05.750 --> 00:15:07.790
Ukulele Ike's real name
was Cliff Edwards.

00:15:07.790 --> 00:15:09.110
He had a very checkered life.

00:15:09.110 --> 00:15:10.180
If you read the book,
I hope people have

00:15:10.180 --> 00:15:10.670
copies of the book.

00:15:10.670 --> 00:15:13.060
You'll see there's a whole
chapter on Ukulele Ike, Cliff

00:15:13.060 --> 00:15:15.680
Edwards, and his sad life.

00:15:15.680 --> 00:15:17.570
He was born in the
same town as Mark

00:15:17.570 --> 00:15:20.090
Twain, Hannibal, Missouri.

00:15:20.090 --> 00:15:21.290
In fact, he met Mark Twain.

00:15:21.290 --> 00:15:23.420
But anyway, in the '20s he
became very popular with his

00:15:23.420 --> 00:15:25.990
records playing his ukulele.

00:15:25.990 --> 00:15:28.700
And then in the '30s, he
made lots of films.

00:15:28.700 --> 00:15:32.840
He's probably best known today
because he lent his voice to

00:15:32.840 --> 00:15:37.010
the sound of Jiminy Cricket in
"Pinocchio." He sings, very

00:15:37.010 --> 00:15:40.110
sweetly, "When You Wish Upon a
Star" in the opening credits

00:15:40.110 --> 00:15:41.030
of that film.

00:15:41.030 --> 00:15:42.110
That's Cliff Edwards.

00:15:42.110 --> 00:15:43.000
He died.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:43.925
He was a gambler.

00:15:43.925 --> 00:15:45.710
He had trouble with his wives.

00:15:45.710 --> 00:15:46.800
He had so many wives.

00:15:46.800 --> 00:15:50.760
He spent all his money, drink
and gambling, and died

00:15:50.760 --> 00:15:52.570
penniless and unknown
in Hollywood.

00:15:52.570 --> 00:15:54.870
His body lay unclaimed
for days.

00:15:54.870 --> 00:15:56.980
Finally, the Walt Disney company
paid for him to have a

00:15:56.980 --> 00:16:01.035
grave, which is actually out
by Bob Hope Airport now.

00:16:01.035 --> 00:16:03.470
You can go and visit him.

00:16:03.470 --> 00:16:05.310
Ukulele Ike's stuff
is all available--

00:16:05.310 --> 00:16:07.610
are you all enjoying this
talk by the way?

00:16:07.610 --> 00:16:09.390
I can see you all smiling.

00:16:09.390 --> 00:16:13.030
Am I talking too fast?

00:16:13.030 --> 00:16:15.150
One of the results of my stroke
is that I speak too

00:16:15.150 --> 00:16:18.812
fast, and my tongue
gets tripped.

00:16:18.812 --> 00:16:21.670
I trip my tongue, but anyway,
as long as you can hear what

00:16:21.670 --> 00:16:23.970
I'm saying, and I'm being
articulate, that's great.

00:16:23.970 --> 00:16:25.720
I can see all your
smiling faces.

00:16:25.720 --> 00:16:27.100
Well now, we're getting towards

00:16:27.100 --> 00:16:28.410
the end of our examples.

00:16:28.410 --> 00:16:31.420
And I'd love to have
more questions.

00:16:31.420 --> 00:16:34.370
In England, the ukulele was very
popular, largely through

00:16:34.370 --> 00:16:36.410
a man called George Formby.

00:16:36.410 --> 00:16:39.570
He's a hero in England, an
absolute national hero.

00:16:39.570 --> 00:16:42.540
He started recording
in the 1930s.

00:16:42.540 --> 00:16:45.150
He made films, Ealing Films,
which were the most popular

00:16:45.150 --> 00:16:47.360
films in the British
box office.

00:16:47.360 --> 00:16:49.170
And he made songs
in World War II.

00:16:49.170 --> 00:16:50.820
He played a banjo ukulele.

00:16:50.820 --> 00:16:52.520
But it looks like a banjo.

00:16:52.520 --> 00:16:53.790
It has a much stronger sound.

00:16:53.790 --> 00:16:57.510
He had an incredible strum,
which if you go on YouTube,

00:16:57.510 --> 00:16:58.890
you can see people
demonstrate.

00:16:58.890 --> 00:17:00.100
It's very, very hard to do.

00:17:00.100 --> 00:17:01.600
He had a syncopated strum.

00:17:04.700 --> 00:17:07.220
He recorded a lot of politically
incorrect songs.

00:17:07.220 --> 00:17:09.079
He was from the north of
England, I should add, the

00:17:09.079 --> 00:17:10.819
same part of the world
as The Beatles.

00:17:10.819 --> 00:17:13.920
He had a goofy grin
and big teeth.

00:17:13.920 --> 00:17:15.339
He spoke in a North
country accent.

00:17:15.339 --> 00:17:19.349
He used to say, he's turned
out nice again, he-he-he.

00:17:19.349 --> 00:17:21.260
My uncle read some
of his songs.

00:17:21.260 --> 00:17:23.990
My uncle wrote the A-side of
this next song, but it didn't

00:17:23.990 --> 00:17:24.950
become a hit.

00:17:24.950 --> 00:17:29.880
My uncle wrote "Do
De O Do Blues."

00:17:29.880 --> 00:17:32.420
I hope that wasn't
objectionable.

00:17:32.420 --> 00:17:32.930
I don't think so.

00:17:32.930 --> 00:17:34.060
It's just harmless stuff.

00:17:34.060 --> 00:17:38.380
But, of course, in those days,
British were so insular they

00:17:38.380 --> 00:17:42.620
didn't care about offending
anybody.

00:17:42.620 --> 00:17:44.810
And I guess it's not really
offensive, actually.

00:17:44.810 --> 00:17:46.380
But we had our empire.

00:17:46.380 --> 00:17:49.820
And we've lost our empire now.

00:17:49.820 --> 00:17:51.530
Anyway, it won't excuse this
song, except I think his

00:17:51.530 --> 00:17:53.110
playing is very good.

00:17:53.110 --> 00:17:53.850
I hope we have some
more questions.

00:17:53.850 --> 00:17:55.630
I've really enjoyed talking
to you all.

00:17:55.630 --> 00:17:57.210
I thoroughly approve
of Google.

00:17:57.210 --> 00:17:59.475
You're wonderful.

00:17:59.475 --> 00:18:01.730
I wish I understood
the computer more.

00:18:01.730 --> 00:18:04.190
I have a terrible trouble
with typing now

00:18:04.190 --> 00:18:06.280
because of my illness.

00:18:06.280 --> 00:18:07.700
Every other word is a mistake.

00:18:07.700 --> 00:18:10.780
Every other word I type comes
out as a typo, so I have to

00:18:10.780 --> 00:18:11.410
keep going back.

00:18:11.410 --> 00:18:13.600
By the way, if you're
interested, I write regularly

00:18:13.600 --> 00:18:17.060
on my website a thing called
"Letter from Lotusland." I've

00:18:17.060 --> 00:18:18.640
done that for 20 years now.

00:18:18.640 --> 00:18:21.140
There's even a book out, which
you can get on Amazon, called

00:18:21.140 --> 00:18:26.310
"Letters from Lotusland." And
if you just put it into

00:18:26.310 --> 00:18:29.270
Google, just put "Letters from
Lotusland," you'll see Ian

00:18:29.270 --> 00:18:31.860
Whitcomb's "Letter from
Lotusland." And every month, I

00:18:31.860 --> 00:18:33.390
write about what I've
been doing.

00:18:33.390 --> 00:18:35.950
People seem to enjoy it
all over the world.

00:18:35.950 --> 00:18:38.230
I've talked so much about
myself haven't I?

00:18:38.230 --> 00:18:39.660
But anyway, my wife is
a wonderful singer.

00:18:39.660 --> 00:18:43.380
It's on that record, called
"Legends of Ukulele." And once

00:18:43.380 --> 00:18:48.590
I was up in Oregon at a folk
festival, and this woman said

00:18:48.590 --> 00:18:49.560
she was going to
play this song.

00:18:49.560 --> 00:18:50.660
And I said, I'll play it.

00:18:50.660 --> 00:18:51.475
She said, no I'd like to it.

00:18:51.475 --> 00:18:53.590
And she sang it in the most
beautiful, straight away.

00:18:53.590 --> 00:18:55.823
And I thought it's just the most
wonderful thing if you're

00:18:55.823 --> 00:18:57.620
a songwriter if you're somebody
else you don't know

00:18:57.620 --> 00:18:58.680
sing your songs.

00:18:58.680 --> 00:19:00.215
It's just so heartwarming.

