00:20:39.030 --> 00:20:41.690
Jake is a wonderful player,
nice fellow.

00:20:41.690 --> 00:20:46.420
And he's playing the virtuosic,
virtuoso, playing

00:20:46.420 --> 00:20:48.470
tunes on the ukulele, which is
completely different to what I

00:20:48.470 --> 00:20:48.880
was playing.

00:20:48.880 --> 00:20:50.630
But, I mean, there's
room for us all.

00:20:50.630 --> 00:20:54.330
Ukulele is a very versatile
instrument indeed.

00:20:54.330 --> 00:20:55.470
Any more questions?

00:20:55.470 --> 00:20:56.301
Yes?

00:20:56.301 --> 00:21:03.035
AUDIENCE: Any history of
ukulele in the blues?

00:21:03.035 --> 00:21:04.960
IAN WHITCOMB: I don't think it
lends itself to the blues.

00:21:04.960 --> 00:21:05.940
It's too happy and jolly.

00:21:05.940 --> 00:21:07.260
It doesn't get blue,
the ukulele.

00:21:07.260 --> 00:21:10.490
Although there is a book, Fred
Sokolow's put out a book of

00:21:10.490 --> 00:21:12.340
playing the blues
on the ukulele.

00:21:12.340 --> 00:21:15.170
But, to me, it's not really--

00:21:15.170 --> 00:21:17.610
its notes are very
short and sharp.

00:21:17.610 --> 00:21:19.240
It doesn't really lend
itself to that.

00:21:19.240 --> 00:21:20.590
It's just, you know-

00:21:20.590 --> 00:21:22.830
[UKULELE PLAYING]

00:21:22.830 --> 00:21:23.055
IAN WHITCOMB: [SINGING]

00:21:23.055 --> 00:21:27.900
I hate to see, the evening
sun go down.

00:21:27.900 --> 00:21:29.930
It's too jolly.

00:21:29.930 --> 00:21:30.650
an instrument.

00:21:30.650 --> 00:21:32.410
Anyway, any more questions?

00:21:32.410 --> 00:21:32.905
Yes?

00:21:32.905 --> 00:21:36.720
AUDIENCE: I have a text from
my cousin in Miami who is a

00:21:36.720 --> 00:21:39.520
ukulele player, which is one of
the reasons I actually came

00:21:39.520 --> 00:21:41.970
today, because he oftentimes
will bring it to family

00:21:41.970 --> 00:21:43.350
gatherings and that
sort of thing.

00:21:43.350 --> 00:21:46.750
And he says, probably too late
now, just thank him for me for

00:21:46.750 --> 00:21:47.896
bringing the uke to
so many folks.

00:21:47.896 --> 00:21:48.470
IAN WHITCOMB: Oh, how good.

00:21:48.470 --> 00:21:49.660
That's nice to hear that.

00:21:49.660 --> 00:21:52.303
AUDIENCE: And he has a YouTube
video he wants me to share

00:21:52.303 --> 00:21:54.190
with you later.

00:21:54.190 --> 00:21:56.430
IAN WHITCOMB: Well, in my own
small way, I'm quite popular

00:21:56.430 --> 00:21:58.430
throughout the world.

00:21:58.430 --> 00:22:00.100
I mean, I've done
so many things.

00:22:00.100 --> 00:22:02.480
By the way, what we didn't
mention was I produced a CD

00:22:02.480 --> 00:22:04.820
which won a Grammy of the
music played aboard the

00:22:04.820 --> 00:22:08.950
"Titanic," which
is a lovely CD.

00:22:08.950 --> 00:22:12.190
I decided that I'd worked on
the James Cameron film.

00:22:12.190 --> 00:22:13.550
I knew he'd got it all
wrong at the end.

00:22:13.550 --> 00:22:16.360
They did not play "Nearer, My
God, to Thee" at the end.

00:22:16.360 --> 00:22:17.940
If a ship is sinking,
you don't play that.

00:22:17.940 --> 00:22:19.960
You play something
jolly and happy.

00:22:19.960 --> 00:22:22.160
So they actually played a song
called "Songe d'Automne." So I

00:22:22.160 --> 00:22:24.820
went to Rhino Records, and I
said, look, why don't we make

00:22:24.820 --> 00:22:27.650
a record to come out the same
time as "Titanic," the film.

00:22:27.650 --> 00:22:29.380
We will have the music that
was actually played

00:22:29.380 --> 00:22:30.060
aboard the real ship.

00:22:30.060 --> 00:22:31.460
James Cameron was furious.

00:22:31.460 --> 00:22:35.000
But our record did extremely
well and won a Grammy Award.

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:37.680
It's a lovely record called
"Titanic, Music as Played on

00:22:37.680 --> 00:22:38.420
the Fateful Voyage."

00:22:38.420 --> 00:22:39.690
So I've done many,
many things.

00:22:39.690 --> 00:22:41.620
I've even, believe it or
not, been in films.

00:22:41.620 --> 00:22:44.650
You can see me in the film
"Contact." I played a BBC

00:22:44.650 --> 00:22:47.450
reporter in that.

00:22:47.450 --> 00:22:51.700
I did the music for "The Cat's
Meow" for Peter Bogdanovich.

00:22:51.700 --> 00:22:53.980
And other films which
we won't mention.

00:22:53.980 --> 00:22:55.610
But I do act.

00:22:55.610 --> 00:22:57.390
I do all these things.

00:22:57.390 --> 00:22:58.940
Write my books.

00:22:58.940 --> 00:23:00.160
But right now I'm sort
of just trying

00:23:00.160 --> 00:23:01.350
to get better, recovery.

00:23:01.350 --> 00:23:03.520
But I've really enjoyed talking
to you all today.

00:23:03.520 --> 00:23:05.010
So nice to see your
happy faces.

00:23:05.010 --> 00:23:06.630
Hope you've enjoyed it too.

00:23:06.630 --> 00:23:07.340
Any more questions?

00:23:07.340 --> 00:23:08.150
Do we have time still?

00:23:08.150 --> 00:23:08.933
AUDIENCE: You did a
couple different

00:23:08.933 --> 00:23:12.671
styles of ukulele playing.

00:23:12.671 --> 00:23:16.800
I was wondering, since you
mentioned the slide guitar

00:23:16.800 --> 00:23:18.120
starting out in Hawaii.

00:23:18.120 --> 00:23:20.880
IAN WHITCOMB: Yes, well
that was Hawaiian.

00:23:20.880 --> 00:23:24.190
That was my friend Fred was
playing a dobro guitar.

00:23:24.190 --> 00:23:28.140
But the earlier Hawaiian
recording was a regular guitar

00:23:28.140 --> 00:23:30.900
which they tuned to open
strings, and then he slid a

00:23:30.900 --> 00:23:32.520
metal bar along.

00:23:32.520 --> 00:23:35.870
That really was a Hawaiian
invention, not from blues at

00:23:35.870 --> 00:23:37.410
all, but from Hawaii.

00:23:37.410 --> 00:23:41.568
AUDIENCE: Did that change how
people played the ukulele?

00:23:41.568 --> 00:23:42.970
IAN WHITCOMB: No, I think they
just strummed along.

00:23:42.970 --> 00:23:44.530
I think it's important, when
you've got a slide guitar

00:23:44.530 --> 00:23:46.260
playing, you really have
to have the ukulele

00:23:46.260 --> 00:23:47.760
play a steady rhythm.

00:23:47.760 --> 00:23:49.680
Otherwise it all gets thrown.

00:23:49.680 --> 00:23:51.020
You have to have them play
a steady rhythm.

00:23:51.020 --> 00:23:52.040
I used to have a very
good strum.

00:23:52.040 --> 00:23:53.670
I'm sure it'll come
back in time.

00:23:53.670 --> 00:23:57.890
But my strum's a bit rudimentary
right now.

00:23:57.890 --> 00:24:00.870
I'm playing this weekend at a
place that's near Cantalina's.

00:24:00.870 --> 00:24:02.490
It's called Boulevard Music.

00:24:02.490 --> 00:24:04.720
It's a folk place.

00:24:04.720 --> 00:24:07.470
With Janet Klein and
her Parlor Boys.

00:24:07.470 --> 00:24:08.880
I'm one of her Parlor Boys.

00:24:08.880 --> 00:24:11.026
I'm a bit old to be
a boy, but still.

00:24:11.026 --> 00:24:13.150
I still play a lot.

00:24:13.150 --> 00:24:17.836
I still play all over the place
with my radio shows.

00:24:17.836 --> 00:24:19.920
I can see somebody's bursting
with a question.

00:24:19.920 --> 00:24:21.340
Are you?

00:24:21.340 --> 00:24:22.860
I hope you've all
enjoyed today.

00:24:22.860 --> 00:24:23.633
Yes?

00:24:23.633 --> 00:24:25.445
AUDIENCE: I've asked this from
several who we've spoke to,

00:24:25.445 --> 00:24:28.140
what do you want to do
when you grow up?

00:24:28.140 --> 00:24:30.770
IAN WHITCOMB: I never
did grow up.

00:24:30.770 --> 00:24:32.560
I've never had a proper job.

00:24:32.560 --> 00:24:36.320
By the way, I went to university
at Trinity College

00:24:36.320 --> 00:24:39.060
in Dublin, which I believe
Google has a big base there

00:24:39.060 --> 00:24:40.880
now in the tallest building in
Dublin, which was not there

00:24:40.880 --> 00:24:44.310
when I was- I was there
from 1961 to '65.

00:24:44.310 --> 00:24:47.080
And Dublin then was a
very old-fashioned,

00:24:47.080 --> 00:24:48.970
priest-ridden country.

00:24:48.970 --> 00:24:50.930
It was run by the
Catholic church.

00:24:50.930 --> 00:24:51.390
You couldn't have

00:24:51.390 --> 00:24:54.020
contraceptives there, for example.

00:24:54.020 --> 00:24:56.780
So it was still set in
the 18th century.

00:24:56.780 --> 00:24:57.800
It was very nice.

00:24:57.800 --> 00:24:59.330
The buildings were all
exactly the same.

00:24:59.330 --> 00:25:00.585
The pubs were very
old-fashioned.

00:25:00.585 --> 00:25:03.380
You'd watch the man pouring your
Guiness, and it was an

00:25:03.380 --> 00:25:06.400
art form skimming the top
of the foam off the top.

00:25:06.400 --> 00:25:10.340
Pouring a Guiness was
really an art form.

00:25:10.340 --> 00:25:12.740
Dublin was a completely
different place then.

00:25:12.740 --> 00:25:14.740
If you went to see a film
there, you used to have

00:25:14.740 --> 00:25:19.030
commissionaires, men in uniform,
standing outside.

00:25:19.030 --> 00:25:22.590
And there were always lines
for films in those days

00:25:22.590 --> 00:25:24.010
because everybody wanted
to see films.

00:25:24.010 --> 00:25:25.620
And the films were all censored
so they couldn't have

00:25:25.620 --> 00:25:27.390
anything that had sex in it.

00:25:27.390 --> 00:25:31.340
And so whenever there was a cut
in the film, the audience

00:25:31.340 --> 00:25:32.740
would shout out, snip! snip!

00:25:32.740 --> 00:25:35.720
Because they thought
it'd been cut.

00:25:35.720 --> 00:25:37.250
It was a very old-fashioned
country.

00:25:37.250 --> 00:25:40.110
In some ways wonderful,
many ways.

00:25:40.110 --> 00:25:42.050
But I had a wonderful time
there, spent most of my time

00:25:42.050 --> 00:25:43.650
in pubs and bars.

00:25:43.650 --> 00:25:48.810
I took a history degree there
in modern history,

00:25:48.810 --> 00:25:51.400
which ended in 1914.

00:25:51.400 --> 00:25:54.450
Went from the fall of the
Roman Empire to 1914.

00:25:54.450 --> 00:25:56.810
And political science, didn't
learn much from that.

00:25:56.810 --> 00:25:59.380
Most of the time I was playing
in bands in Dublin.

00:25:59.380 --> 00:26:01.690
But I had a wonderful
time in Dublin.

00:26:01.690 --> 00:26:03.880
And my best friends
I met there.

00:26:03.880 --> 00:26:05.310
I really loved Ireland.

00:26:05.310 --> 00:26:05.710
I still do.

00:26:05.710 --> 00:26:09.190
I'm going back there in
August to play at

00:26:09.190 --> 00:26:11.750
ukulele hulee there.

00:26:11.750 --> 00:26:13.340
Why they've hired me I
don't know because I

00:26:13.340 --> 00:26:13.740
can't play very well.

00:26:13.740 --> 00:26:15.240
But they're very kind
to me there.

00:26:15.240 --> 00:26:17.730
And that's where I made my first
record, which became the

00:26:17.730 --> 00:26:19.170
hit, top 10 hit.

00:26:19.170 --> 00:26:22.423
In Ireland, it was the first
Irish-made record to ever get

00:26:22.423 --> 00:26:24.350
into the charts, which means
there's a link between Ian

00:26:24.350 --> 00:26:25.690
Whitcomb and U2.

00:26:25.690 --> 00:26:29.150
I don't think they like
that connection much.

00:26:29.150 --> 00:26:29.888
Yes?

00:26:29.888 --> 00:26:36.470
AUDIENCE: How hard is
it for a guitar

00:26:36.470 --> 00:26:37.850
player to play the ukulele?

00:26:37.850 --> 00:26:38.900
IAN WHITCOMB: It'd be
going backwards.

00:26:38.900 --> 00:26:40.620
It's much simpler to play.

00:26:40.620 --> 00:26:44.410
It's much simpler than playing
guitar to get a basic strum

00:26:44.410 --> 00:26:46.550
and find those figures.

00:26:46.550 --> 00:26:48.210
It's easy.

00:26:48.210 --> 00:26:51.310
That's why so many people- there
are clubs all over Los

00:26:51.310 --> 00:26:52.970
Angeles, I go to them.

00:26:52.970 --> 00:26:55.370
And they meet once a week,
these strummers.

00:26:55.370 --> 00:26:58.540
And they all sit there, and they
play every kind of song

00:26:58.540 --> 00:27:00.960
from "Bridge Over Troubled
Water" to whatever.

00:27:00.960 --> 00:27:03.230
And they sit there and they
strum and they sing.

00:27:03.230 --> 00:27:05.890
It's a joyous sight to see.

00:27:05.890 --> 00:27:08.330
The ukulele brings nothing
but smiles.

00:27:08.330 --> 00:27:10.810
It's a really happy
instrument.

00:27:10.810 --> 00:27:12.460
I love it.

00:27:12.460 --> 00:27:14.880
I've had some very happy moments
playing the ukulele

00:27:14.880 --> 00:27:15.810
and writing songs.

00:27:15.810 --> 00:27:18.620
I still write songs.

00:27:18.620 --> 00:27:19.790
I mean, songwriting
is really what I'm

00:27:19.790 --> 00:27:20.740
interested in most of all.

00:27:20.740 --> 00:27:22.680
But when I say songwriting, I
mean songs that have proper

00:27:22.680 --> 00:27:23.860
tunes and words.

00:27:23.860 --> 00:27:28.240
I know I sound old-fashioned,
but I can't get along with the

00:27:28.240 --> 00:27:30.490
rap today and hip hop
because it doesn't

00:27:30.490 --> 00:27:32.010
need to have any tunes.

00:27:32.010 --> 00:27:36.750
I mean, if you want to analyze
rap, Winston Churchill was

00:27:36.750 --> 00:27:40.300
actually a rapper because he
just spoke without tunes.

00:27:40.300 --> 00:27:41.780
We shall fight them
on the beaches.

00:27:41.780 --> 00:27:44.300
I mean, that's rapping too.

00:27:44.300 --> 00:27:45.910
He rapped.

00:27:45.910 --> 00:27:47.640
FDR rapped, too.

00:27:47.640 --> 00:27:49.070
The only thing we have to
fear is fear itself.

00:27:49.070 --> 00:27:51.020
That's rapping, really.

00:27:51.020 --> 00:27:52.820
But rapping has nothing
to do songwriting,

00:27:52.820 --> 00:27:54.240
that's what I'm saying.

00:27:54.240 --> 00:27:55.860
It may be saying some
important things.

00:27:55.860 --> 00:27:57.190
I'm not against it from that.

00:27:57.190 --> 00:27:59.410
But the point is it's nothing
to do with music.

00:27:59.410 --> 00:28:00.500
And I've said enough opinions.

00:28:00.500 --> 00:28:02.320
And I'm sure I've shocked
you all today.

00:28:02.320 --> 00:28:05.770
I'm a man of many opinions.

00:28:05.770 --> 00:28:07.110
Thank you very much indeed.

00:28:07.110 --> 00:28:11.690
And don't forget, help
yourself to the

00:28:11.690 --> 00:28:12.940
books and the CDs.

00:28:12.940 --> 00:28:16.610
Anything on stage except my
uke is for you, thank you.

